(438, 1, 'Seminar on The JCM Implementation Accelerating Low Carbon Development Through JCM Scheme', '<p>On 14 February 2018, Institute for Global Environmental Strategies (IGES),&nbsp; Yayasan Mitra Hijau in collaboration with the Coordinating Ministry of Economic Affairs and the JCM secretariat Indonesia jointly organized the annual workshop on Joint Crediting Mechanism (JCM) with theme &ldquo;Accelerating Private Sector Participation towards Low-Carbon Development in Indonesia&rdquo; &nbsp;in Jakarta, Indonesia.</p>\n\n<p>The seminar was attended by more or less 80 participants coming from Indonesian companies, government officials, Indonesian Association, international organization, and representatives of related organizations. The event was opened by Mr. Kentaro Takahashi from IGES and Mr. Edwin Manansang from Coordinating Ministry for Economic Affairs.</p>\n\n<p>In the first session, Mr. Dicky Edwin Hindarto from JCM Secretariat, Mr. Surya Darma from Indonesia Renewable Energy Society, also Mr. Kentaro Takahashi from IGES, and Mr. Feri Agustian from Indesso Aroma Company&nbsp;shared the information about JCM Implementation and how to incorporate with future climate regime. JCM implementation has created a good cooperation between private sectors, the government, and climate change mitigation experts. Through the cooperation of these parties, not only the low carbon development project could be conducted in Indonesia, but also knowledge sharing in the Monitoring, Reporting and Verification (MRV) as well as the advance low carbon technology.</p>\n\n<p>Following the first session, the workshop was continued by a series of presentation delivered by speakers from Government of Indonesia representatives, IGES, and Semen Indonesia representative. In this session, the speakers shared how to implement carbon emission reduction through JCM project in Indonesia particularly energy conservation and efficiency which played a significant role in a climate change mitigation actions.</p>\n\n<p>Lastly, from the workshop it is mentioned that JCM implementation is implemented between Japan and 17 countries. Throughout the implementation of JCM among countries, there are 25 project registered as JCM projects with 100 projects are approved to be financially supported by Government of Japan, with 50 methodologies approved as JCM methodologies. In addition to the given information, IGES also stated that for the next fiscal year the budget will be allocated for model project is 71 Million USD and thus far, IGES has supported the implementation of 40 methodologies development.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>---------</p>\n\n<p><br />\n*Presentation materials can be download&nbsp;<a href=\"http://jcm.ekon.go.id/en/index.php/content/MzY%253D/presentation_materials\">here</a></p>', 'uploads/modules/1/438.jpg', NULL, 4, 'active', 'SysAdmin', '2018-02-21 23:13:21', 'SysAdmin', '2018-08-09 01:13:24'),
(439, 1, 'Semen Indonesia WHRPG Project Inspection Meeting on February 2018', '<p>On February 27, 2018, a Waste Heat Recovery Power Generation (WHRPG) project inspection meeting was held at PT Semen Indonesia, Tuban, East Java. PTSI was visited by Global Enviromental Center (GEC) Foundation CEO, Kunihiro Suga as representative of Japan&#39;s Ministry of Environment, Head of Joint Crediting Mechanism (JCM) Secretariat, Dicky Edwin Hindarto and Head of Deputy for Multilateral Economic Cooperation and Financing of Coordinating Ministry for Economic Affairs, Cahyadi Yudadahono.</p>\n\n<p>Mr. Tri Abdisatrio, director of engineering and production&nbsp;said that Semen Indonesia is undertaking an energy efficiency program with the development of Waste Heat Recovery Power Generation (WHRPG). WHRPG that has been planned since 2014, utilizing exhaust gas from the production process into electrical energy. Currently, Semen Indonesia has built two WHRPG facilities, namely Indarung Padang factory with a capacity of 8.6 MW and Tuban factory of East Java with a capacity of 30.6 MW. The WHPRG project is not only environmentally friendly but can also save up to 15% electricity usage costs. In addition, this cooperation provides transfer knowledge between PTSI engineering and JFE engineering, especially for the WHPRG project in the cement industry.</p>\n\n<p>Mr. Cahyadi Yudadahono stated that the cooperation of the Indonesian government with Japan had taken place long before the Paris agreement. Precisely in 2013, has agreed bilateral cooperation between japan and indonesia for carbon emission reduction project. This cooperation is applied in JCM projects that focus on energy efficiency. The Government of Indonesia expects this project to have a positive impact on all sectors in accordance with the prevailing regulations. The government hopes for significant progress and bring benefits to the country, especially to reduce the potential for climate change.</p>\n\n<p>Meanwhile, CEO of Global Enviromental Center (GEC) Foundation, Mr. Kunihiro Suga said he was satisfied with the results of WHRPG development at Tuban plant. &quot;I have seen the results of the WHRPG project activity by going up and down the stairs, The project is well executed and we will report the results to the Government of Japan&quot; Mr. Kunihiro Said. The development of WHRPG Tuban plant is a partnership between the Government of Indonesia and the Japanese government through the Joint Crediting Mechanism (JCM) scheme. The Japanese government provides a subsidy of US $ 11 million for the construction of this WHRPG.</p>\n\n<p>Project manager PT. Cement Indonesia, Mr. Heru Indrawidjajanto stated that the WHR system will utilize waste heat currently emitted from the cement factory without utilization. WHR boilers will generate steam from the waste heat exhausted from the cement plant, and the steam will be fed to the steam turbine generator to generate electricity. WHR system consists of a Suspension Preheater boiler (SP boiler),&nbsp;Air Quenching Cooler boiler (AQC boiler), turbine generator and cooling tower. The project will contribute to a CO2 emission reduction program of 122,358 ton CO2 / year or equivalent to planting 4,295 trembesi trees in 96 hectares of land. It is planned that the WHRPG will begin operating in April 2018. The WHR system is expected to spread out in the Indonesian industry and it will contribute to sustainable development not only in environmental aspect but also economical aspect.</p>\n\n<p>Mr. Sumito Sakabe of GEC stated that all of the engineering procedures and tools in the WHPRG project have been operating well. Currently, the WHPRG project is still in the experimental stage and this project will be periodically monitored by JFE engineering. JFE Engineering Corporation Japan is a leading company in environmental technology including Waste Heat Recovery Power Generation (WHRPG). JFE has contributed a lot in Indonesia through environmentally friendly technologies such as WHRPG and Geothermal Power Generation. Mr. Sumito added, very pleased to see the evidence of cooperation through the installation of project information in each plant.</p>', 'uploads/modules/1/439.jpg', NULL, 3, 'archieved', 'SysAdmin', '2018-02-27 20:08:59', 'SysAdmin', '2019-02-14 19:08:15'),
